# Stepper Motor Control with LCD and Encoder

This Arduino sketch demonstrates controlling two stepper motors using the HiLetgo 3D Printer Reprap Smart Controller 12864 LCD Display, an encoder, and a button. The stepper motors are connected through the RAMPS 1.4 Arduino Mega shield.

## Hardware Requirements
- Arduino Mega board
- RAMPS 1.4 shield
- HiLetgo 3D Printer Reprap Smart Controller 12864 LCD Display
- Two stepper motors
- Two end stop switches
- Buzzer
- Encoder

## Circuit Diagram
Insert a circuit diagram here to illustrate the connections between the components.

## Installation and Usage
1. Connect the components according to the circuit diagram.
2. Open the Arduino IDE.
3. Install the U8glib and AccelStepper libraries if not already installed.
4. Open the `stepper_control.ino` sketch.
5. Select the appropriate board and port from the Arduino IDE.
6. Upload the sketch to the Arduino board.
7. Monitor the LCD display for the motor control and distance readings.

## Functionality
- The LCD display shows "Hello, World!" on the screen.
- Adjust the speed of stepper1 using the encoder.
- Press the button to activate the buzzer.
- The distance encoder measures wire distance and displays the value on the LCD screen.
- Two end stop switches change the direction of the corresponding stepper motor when activated.

## Customization
- Adjust the pin connections according to your wiring setup.
- Modify the `MAX_SPEED` and `ACCELERATION` constants to change the speed and acceleration of the stepper motors.
- Customize the LCD messages and formatting as needed.
- Adapt the code to your specific requirements and additional functionality.

